{
  "What is the term for an organism that makes its own food, usually through photosynthesis?": "",
  "Producer (autotroph)": "",
  "Decomposer": "",
  "Predator": "",
  "Consumer": "",
  "Producers (autotrophs) make their own food, primarily through photosynthesis. They form the base of every food chain and include plants, algae, and some bacteria.": "",
  "What is the approximate percentage of energy that transfers from one trophic level to the next?": "",
  "100%": "",
  "90%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "10%": "",
  "The 10% rule (Lindeman's efficiency) states that only about 10% of energy at one trophic level is transferred to the next. The remaining 90% is lost primarily as heat through cellular respiration.": "",
  "What type of organism obtains energy by eating other organisms?": "",
  "Consumer (heterotroph)": "",
  "Chemosynthetic bacterium": "",
  "Consumers (heterotrophs) obtain energy by eating other organisms. They include herbivores (eat plants), carnivores (eat animals), and omnivores (eat both).": "",
  "What is a trophic level?": "",
  "The rate of decomposition in soil": "",
  "Each step in a food chain where energy is transferred": "",
  "The total amount of energy in an ecosystem": "",
  "A type of symbiotic relationship": "",
  "A trophic level is each step in a food chain where energy is transferred from one group of organisms to another. Producers are the first trophic level, primary consumers the second, and so on.": "",
  "What happens to the approximately 90% of energy that is NOT transferred to the next trophic level?": "",
  "It is converted to light energy": "",
  "It is lost as heat through metabolic processes": "",
  "It is recycled back to the producers": "",
  "It is stored permanently in the soil": "",
  "At each trophic level, roughly 90% of energy is lost as heat through cellular respiration and other metabolic processes. Unlike nutrients, energy cannot be recycled and must be continuously replenished by the sun or chemosynthesis.": "",
  "What type of organism breaks down dead organic material and recycles nutrients?": "",
  "Primary consumer": "",
  "Top predator": "",
  "Producer": "",
  "Decomposers (such as fungi and bacteria) break down dead organisms and waste products, releasing nutrients back into the soil and atmosphere for producers to reuse.": "",
  "Why do food chains rarely have more than 4-5 trophic levels?": "",
  "Too little energy remains to support additional levels": "",
  "Predators prefer not to eat other predators": "",
  "There are not enough species in most ecosystems": "",
  "Decomposers consume all organisms before a 6th level can form": "",
  "With only 10% of energy transferred at each level, the energy available becomes too small to sustain populations after 4-5 transfers. Starting with 10,000 kcal at producers, only 1 kcal would remain after five transfers.": "",
  "What is gross primary productivity (GPP)?": "",
  "The total amount of energy fixed by producers through photosynthesis": "",
  "The energy available to consumers after producers' respiration": "",
  "The total biomass of all consumers in an ecosystem": "",
  "The rate at which decomposers break down dead matter": "",
  "Gross primary productivity (GPP) is the total amount of energy captured by producers through photosynthesis. Net primary productivity (NPP) is GPP minus the energy producers use for their own respiration.": "",
  "Which process powers ecosystems in environments without sunlight, such as deep-sea hydrothermal vents?": "",
  "Combustion": "",
  "Chemosynthesis": "",
  "Photosynthesis": "",
  "Fermentation": "",
  "Chemosynthesis uses energy from chemical reactions (such as oxidizing hydrogen sulfide) to produce organic molecules. Chemosynthetic bacteria are the primary producers at hydrothermal vents and other sunlight-free environments.": "",
  "What is biomagnification?": "",
  "The amplification of energy at each trophic level": "",
  "The increase in biodiversity along food chains": "",
  "The increasing concentration of toxins at higher trophic levels": "",
  "The decrease in organism size at higher trophic levels": "",
  "Biomagnification is the process by which persistent toxins (such as DDT and mercury) become more concentrated at each higher trophic level, because organisms consume many prey items that each contain the toxin.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a producer?": "",
  "An organism that makes its own food, usually through photosynthesis or chemosynthesis": "",
  "An organism that hunts and kills other organisms for food": "",
  "An organism that breaks down dead organic material": "",
  "An organism that obtains energy by eating other organisms": "",
  "Producers (autotrophs) make their own food from inorganic sources, either through photosynthesis (using sunlight) or chemosynthesis (using chemical energy). They form the foundation of all food chains and food webs.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a consumer?": "",
  "An organism that converts sunlight to chemical energy": "",
  "An organism that makes its own food through photosynthesis": "",
  "An organism that breaks down dead matter in soil": "",
  "Consumers (heterotrophs) cannot make their own food and must obtain energy by eating other organisms. They are classified by what they eat: herbivores eat plants, carnivores eat animals, and omnivores eat both.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a decomposer?": "",
  "An organism at the top of the food chain": "",
  "An organism that produces food through photosynthesis": "",
  "An organism that forms symbiotic relationships with plants": "",
  "An organism that breaks down dead organic material, recycling nutrients back into the ecosystem": "",
  "Decomposers (primarily fungi and bacteria) break down dead organisms and waste, releasing inorganic nutrients back into the soil and atmosphere. They are the essential link between energy flow and nutrient cycling.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a trophic level?": "",
  "The total number of species present in an ecosystem": "",
  "Each step in a food chain or food web where energy is transferred from one group of organisms to another": "",
  "The reproductive rate of a population": "",
  "The physical location where an organism lives": "",
  "Trophic levels represent the feeding positions in a food chain. The first trophic level is occupied by producers, the second by primary consumers (herbivores), the third by secondary consumers, and so on.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the 10% rule?": "",
  "Only about 10% of energy at one trophic level is transferred to the next level": "",
  "10% of sunlight reaching Earth is used in photosynthesis": "",
  "Ecosystems lose 10% of their species every decade": "",
  "10% of all species in an ecosystem are producers": "",
  "The 10% rule (Lindeman's efficiency) states that approximately 10% of energy is passed from one trophic level to the next. The remaining 90% is lost primarily as heat through cellular respiration. This limits the number of trophic levels an ecosystem can support.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes net primary productivity (NPP)?": "",
  "The rate at which consumers convert food to body mass": "",
  "The energy remaining in producers after subtracting the energy they use for their own respiration": "",
  "The total biomass of all organisms in an ecosystem": "",
  "Net primary productivity (NPP) equals gross primary productivity (GPP) minus the energy used by producers for their own respiration. NPP represents the energy stored in plant biomass that is actually available to herbivores and the rest of the food web.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a food web?": "",
  "A complex network of interconnected food chains showing multiple feeding relationships in an ecosystem": "",
  "A single linear sequence of organisms where each is eaten by the next": "",
  "The total amount of food available in an ecosystem": "",
  "A diagram showing only the top predators in an ecosystem": "",
  "A food web shows the complex network of feeding relationships in an ecosystem. Unlike a simple food chain, a food web reveals that most organisms eat and are eaten by multiple species, providing redundancy and resilience.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes biomagnification?": "",
  "The increase in biodiversity from one ecosystem to another": "",
  "The progressive decrease in organism size at higher trophic levels": "",
  "The conversion of sunlight to chemical energy by producers": "",
  "The process by which concentrations of persistent toxins increase at successively higher trophic levels": "",
  "Biomagnification occurs because persistent toxins are absorbed faster than they can be eliminated. Organisms at higher trophic levels consume many contaminated prey items, accumulating increasingly dangerous concentrations of toxins like DDT and mercury.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a trophic cascade?": "",
  "The sequential extinction of species from the bottom of the food chain": "",
  "The process of nutrient cycling through the atmosphere and soil": "",
  "A chain of indirect effects caused by adding or removing a top predator that ripples through multiple trophic levels": "",
  "A waterfall of energy that flows from producers to top consumers": "",
  "A trophic cascade occurs when changes at one trophic level trigger a series of effects down through lower levels. The reintroduction of wolves to Yellowstone is a famous example: wolves reduced elk numbers, which allowed willows to regrow, which brought back beavers.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes secondary production?": "",
  "The energy recycled by decomposers from dead organic matter": "",
  "The total energy fixed by the second trophic level through photosynthesis": "",
  "The amount of energy converted to new biomass by consumers through growth and reproduction": "",
  "The rate at which producers regenerate after being consumed": "",
  "Secondary production is the energy stored in consumer biomass through growth and reproduction. It is the only portion of a consumer's energy budget available to the next trophic level — the rest is lost to respiration and feces.": "",
  "A Serengeti grassland captures 20,000 kcal/m² of solar energy per year through photosynthesis. Using the 10% rule, approximately how much energy would be available to zebras (primary consumers)?": "",
  "200 kcal/m²": "",
  "10,000 kcal/m²": "",
  "2,000 kcal/m²": "",
  "18,000 kcal/m²": "",
  "The 10% rule states that only 10% of energy at one trophic level transfers to the next. With producers capturing 20,000 kcal/m², primary consumers would have approximately 2,000 kcal/m² available. The remaining 90% is lost as heat through cellular respiration.": "",
  "Scientists discover thriving ecosystems around deep-sea hydrothermal vents where no sunlight reaches. Giant tube worms and crabs cluster around bacterial mats near superheated water. What is the ultimate energy source for these communities?": "",
  "Chemical energy from hydrogen sulfide via chemosynthesis": "",
  "Geothermal heat directly absorbed by organisms": "",
  "Sunlight that filters down from the surface": "",
  "Organic matter drifting from surface ecosystems": "",
  "Chemosynthetic bacteria oxidize hydrogen sulfide and other inorganic chemicals from hydrothermal vents to produce organic molecules. These bacteria are the primary producers of vent communities, supporting food chains without any sunlight input.": "",
  "An Antarctic food chain: phytoplankton → krill → penguins → leopard seals → orcas. If phytoplankton fix 100,000 kcal, approximately how much energy reaches the orcas?": "",
  "10 kcal — after four 10% transfers": "",
  "10,000 kcal based on the": "",
  "1,000 kcal when evaluated": "",
  "100 kcal, particularly": "",
  "Applying the 10% rule at each transfer: 100,000 → 10,000 (krill) → 1,000 (penguins) → 100 (seals) → 10 kcal (orcas). After four transfers, only 0.01% of original energy remains. This explains why top predators need enormous ranges and why food chains rarely exceed 4-5 levels.": "",
  "DDT concentrations in a lake: water 0.04 ppm, algae 0.5 ppm, small fish 2 ppm, large fish 25 ppm, ospreys 1,600 ppm. This 40,000-fold increase from water to top predators nearly drove bald eagles to extinction. What process caused this?": "",
  "Bioaccumulation — each organism independently absorbs DDT from water": "",
  "Decomposition — DDT was released from dead prey organisms": "",
  "Biomagnification — persistent toxins concentrate at higher trophic levels because they are absorbed faster than eliminated": "",
  "Eutrophication — excess nutrients amplified DDT production": "",
  "Biomagnification causes persistent toxins to concentrate at each higher trophic level. Ospreys eat many large fish, each of which consumed many small fish, so DDT accumulated 40,000-fold from water to top predator. DDT caused eggshell thinning that nearly drove eagles and ospreys to extinction before its ban.": "",
  "A farmer produces 5,000 kg of grain per hectare. Eating grain directly supports ~500 kg of human biomass. If grain is fed to cattle first, approximately how much human biomass can the same hectare support?": "",
  "About 5 kg — two extra trophic levels cause 99% loss": "",
  "About 250 kg — cattle convert grain efficiently": "",
  "About 50 kg — an additional 90% energy loss occurs when feeding cattle": "",
  "About 500 kg — beef has the same energy as grain": "",
  "Adding cattle as an intermediary trophic level means another 90% energy loss: 500 kg × 10% = ~50 kg. This is a direct application of the 10% rule showing why eating lower on the food chain is more efficient and uses less land.": "",
  "After groupers are overfished from a coral reef, parrotfish populations boom then crash, and algae overgrow to smother the coral. This chain of events demonstrates:": "",
  "Groupers provided essential nutrients for coral growth": "",
  "Groupers directly consumed algae, so their loss allowed overgrowth": "",
  "Removing top predators destabilizes lower trophic levels, disrupting energy flow through the entire food web": "",
  "Biomagnification of toxins poisoned the parrotfish": "",
  "This trophic cascade shows how changes at one level ripple through the entire web. Losing groupers destabilized parrotfish populations, which destabilized algae control, ultimately smothering coral. Complex food webs require intact trophic levels for stable energy flow.": "",
  "The open ocean has LOW phytoplankton biomass but HIGH productivity, while a kelp forest has high biomass but slow turnover. The open ocean shows an inverted biomass pyramid. Why?": "",
  "The 10% rule does not apply in marine ecosystems": "",
  "Phytoplankton reproduce so rapidly that their high turnover supports greater zooplankton biomass despite low standing crop": "",
  "Zooplankton supplement their energy through photosynthesis": "",
  "Ocean currents bring extra energy from other ecosystems": "",
  "Inverted biomass pyramids occur when producers have extremely high turnover rates. Phytoplankton divide daily, producing enough cumulative energy to support greater zooplankton biomass. The energy pyramid is never inverted, but standing biomass can be when production rate outpaces accumulation.": "",
  "An energy budget for a white-tailed deer: 1,000 kcal consumed, 300 kcal in feces, 600 kcal for cellular respiration, 100 kcal converted to new body mass. What term describes the 100 kcal, and why does it matter?": "",
  "Metabolic efficiency — it measures how well the deer processes food": "",
  "Gross primary production — it represents total energy captured": "",
  "Trophic efficiency — it determines the deer's position in the food chain": "",
  "Secondary production — it is the only energy available to the next trophic level (predators)": "",
  "The 100 kcal stored as new biomass is secondary production — the only energy available to predators at the next trophic level. The 300 kcal in feces feeds decomposers and detritivores, while the 600 kcal from respiration is irreversibly lost as heat.": "",
  "Warming ocean temperatures are reducing phytoplankton populations, which contribute roughly 50% of Earth's total photosynthesis. What is the most significant consequence for global energy flow?": "",
  "Marine organisms would switch to chemosynthesis as an alternative": "",
  "Land-based producers would immediately replace the lost ocean productivity": "",
  "Higher trophic levels would increase their own photosynthesis to compensate": "",
  "Reduced primary productivity shrinks the energy base supporting all marine food webs": "",
  "Phytoplankton are the foundation of nearly all ocean food webs and contribute ~50% of global photosynthesis. Their decline reduces the total energy entering marine ecosystems, meaning less energy flows to every subsequent trophic level. Additionally, reduced phytoplankton means less CO₂ absorption, potentially accelerating climate change in a positive feedback loop.": "",
  "In Lake Victoria, the introduced Nile perch replaced hundreds of native cichlid species that occupied various trophic roles — herbivores, detritivores, and small predators. How did this invasion most likely affect the lake's energy flow?": "",
  "It had no effect because total biomass was maintained": "",
  "It shortened food chains and disrupted multiple energy pathways, reducing ecosystem resilience": "",
  "It caused energy to flow backward through the food web": "",
  "It increased overall ecosystem productivity by adding a new top predator": "",
  "The Nile perch collapsed complex energy pathways into a simplified chain by eliminating cichlids occupying many trophic roles. Without herbivorous cichlids, algal blooms increased; without detritivorous cichlids, decomposition pathways were disrupted. This demonstrates how biodiversity is essential for balanced energy flow and ecosystem resilience.": ""
